causing dynamical symmetry breaking. We will assume a similar result for the dynamically

generated -operators, and take the generic size of a -operator to be 4/ 2. It cannot be much

larger than this because of a unitarity upper bound of 8/ 2 on the size of a 4-fermion

operator [7]. In addition, masses of the gauge bosons in (SU(2) ×U(1) )/U(1) are related to the
V V X

corresponding Goldstone boson decay constants, gf. This shows that the estimate 4/ 2 for

the size of the -operator is consistent with the naive dimensional analysis estimate, which

would give 1/f 2 [8].

Returning to the original question, how much do the -operators contribute to a decay

constant f? Roughly speaking this contribution is determined by a 3-loop diagram involving a -

operator `vertex' and its hermitian conjugate, with the four fermion lines going from one vertex

to the other. We are making an analogy with the derivation of the Pagels-Stokar [9] formula for

f which involves a single quark loop. By using 4/ 2 as the size of the -operators, assigning


a factor of 1/(4)2 to each loop, and by cutting off the integrations at we find a contribution to

f of order /(4)2. This is to be compared to the actual size of f /4 . This means for

example that our -operators contribute very little to the (SU(2) ×U(1) )/U(1) gauge boson
